  <div class="row">
  	<div class="col-md-9">	
   			<div class="article-content ArticleContent" itemprop="articleBody"><p>Merge tags are a feature that allow you to customize a message with details about the event or personalize the message to the person receiving it.</p>

<p>For example, let’s say that you want to include the name of the attendee in the greeting of the message and the start date of the event in the body. Adding those merge tags to the content will be replaced with the actual information of those tags when the message is sent out.</p>

<p><b id="docs-internal-guid-27025606-7fff-9a06-d882-e0dec473b22f"><img height="180" src="https://lh6.googleusercontent.com/uM6yXDi2k9mw4U9cUEKdOFcOqivVp9bQBEyrMFdZb85qJoG5ECVkAg1qZiKc_uyGrUCZ3NH_MdMZ5nQstoKNF8JoykXW7qwjeA3oogvGlmWzSfMFLTsaljnAmBUpDb3kVpPsKV8" width="624" /></b></p>

<h2>Types of Merge Tags</h2>

<p>There are merge tags for several types of information, including Event Details, Ticket Information, Venue Details, and Attendee Data. Merge tags will fall into those categories and are available in the Message Editor to the right of the right of the message subject line and message body.</p>

<p><b id="docs-internal-guid-d2d321d7-7fff-0183-02f3-67ebbd345eb1"><img height="233" src="https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/mmjDAmpNduvfJezYLW_VmW1GpMR62b4sIWxU90xOY2F1E81om8kqYne8zYf1izqZl-lcNtMRUkjqGBEzXcMRYRuq32uHSjTR1PedqQaDC5I0gBXuoiVlMh_UDozorR4IrJObYZA" width="624" /></b></p>

<h2>How to Use Merge Tags</h2>

<p>To add a merge tag to a message, make sure your cursor is where you want the tag to appear in the message, then click on the tag in the toolbar that contains the merge tags. That’s it! The merge tag will display in the message editor and be replaced with real data when the message is sent.</p>

<p><b id="docs-internal-guid-627898c3-7fff-2545-cb4a-7af53cd8ed11"><img height="293" src="https://lh6.googleusercontent.com/3sb76_FSwN0jA1E9Tb5RfAStsJ5_Siw60_C56l1tYciTpEg4bZU39stlojMJnPbFg96FkoNkFeXCANcnRCSFGYOf87yZIdKW4cn6eL-0famOQYsoGy7O_Y1q8IOrcdiVY4TlS5Y" width="624" /></b></p>

<h2>Preview Merge Tags</h2>

<p>It’s always a good idea to preview a message to make sure everything looks good and you have a chance to edit it before it is sent to attendees.</p>

<p>Use the Preview link at the top of the Message Editor to see an example of the message with merge tags in brackets where the data will go.</p>

<p><b id="docs-internal-guid-9d497b4a-7fff-7eff-911a-855191779f4b"><img height="268" src="https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/8D708abfU1N41MtdZQg2y44GWg8y4C2D2kwSfjWhqyOKtf8hzPSOV8Fo9u2uk40tJYMbHVoPDor_ZOXjTMb_px5BvlfQ4fHPWZVkuc0Ciy8Tzrbff2VKwrMJIVfJP6ZcWcNYreM" width="624" /></b></p>

<h2>Merge Tag Cheat Sheet</h2>

<p>Promoter includes many merge tags to help you customize a message with dynamic content. Here’s a quick reference you can use to see them all in one place and what each one does.</p>

<h3>Events</h3>

<p>The merge tags in this section include details about the event related to the message.</p>

<table>
	<thead>
		<tr>
			<th>Merge Tag</th>
			<th>Description</th>
		</tr>
	</thead>
	<tbody>
		<tr>
			<td>Event Title</td>
			<td>Adds the title of the event to the message.</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td>Event Excerpt</td>
			<td>Use this tag to include the WordPress excerpt for the event. If no excerpt is specifically defined for the event, then this tag will use the excerpt that is automatically generated by WordPress.</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td>Event Start Date</td>
			<td>Adds the date the event is scheduled to begin. E.g. July 15</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td>Event Start Time</td>
			<td>Adds the time of day that the event is scheduled to begin. E.g. 10:00 a.m.</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td>Event End Date</td>
			<td>Adds the date the event is scheduled to end. E.g. July 16</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td>Event End Time</td>
			<td>Adds the time of day that the event is scheduled to begin. E.g. 10:00 a.m.</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td>Event URL</td>
			<td>Adds the web address of the event to the message. E.g. your-website.com/link-to-event</td>
		</tr>
	</tbody>
</table>

<h3>&nbsp;</h3>

<h3>Tickets</h3>

<p>The merge tags in this section contain information about tickets that have been created for the event using the Event Tickets / Event Tickets Plus &nbsp;plugin.</p>

<table>
	<thead>
		<tr>
			<th>Merge Tag</th>
			<th>Description</th>
		</tr>
	</thead>
	<tbody>
		<tr>
			<td>Buy Now Link</td>
			<td>Adds a direct link to the ticket form on the event page of your website.</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td>Ticket Name</td>
			<td>Adds the name of the ticket. There are options in the toolbar for each ticket name. For example, if you have one ticket called Early Bird and another ticket called General Admission, then the following options will be available in the toolbar and will output those names, respectively:
			<ul>
				<li>Ticket Name (Early Bird)</li>
				<li>Ticket Name (General Admission)</li>
			</ul>
			</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td>Ticket Price</td>
			<td>Displays the price of a ticket for the event. There are options for each ticket type that has been created for the event. For example, if you have one ticket called Early Bird that is priced at $15 and another ticket called General Admission that is priced at $20, then the following options will be available in the toolbar: `
			<ul>
				<li>Ticket Price (Early Bird): Outputs “15”</li>
				<li>Ticket Price (General Admission): Outputs “20”</li>
			</ul>
			Note that the currency is not included in the output, so be sure to include that either before or after the merge tag, depending on the currency.</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td>Tickets Remaining</td>
			<td>Displays the quantity of tickets that are left to purchase for the event for a particular ticket. For example, if you have a ticket called General Admission that has 100 tickets available and 90 tickets have been purchased, then the option “Tickets Remaining (General Admission)” option will be available in the toolbar and will display “10” in the message.</td>
		</tr>
	</tbody>
</table>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<h3>Event Venue</h3>

<p>The merge tags in this section provide details about the location of the event.</p>

<table>
	<thead>
		<tr>
			<th>Merge Tag</th>
			<th>Description</th>
		</tr>
	</thead>
	<tbody>
		<tr>
			<td>Venue Name</td>
			<td>Displays the name of the venue, if one is available.</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td>Venue Address</td>
			<td>Displays the physical address of the location, as provided by the site.</td>
		</tr>
	</tbody>
</table>

<h3>Attendees</h3>

<p>The merge tags in this section provide details about the attendee receiving the sent message.</p>

<table>
	<thead>
		<tr>
			<th>Merge Tag</th>
			<th>Description</th>
		</tr>
	</thead>
	<tbody>
		<tr>
			<td>Attendee First Name</td>
			<td>Adds the first name of the attendee receiving the message.</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td>Attendee Last Name</td>
			<td>Adds the last name of the attendee receiving the message.</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td>Attendee Email</td>
			<td>Adds the email address of the the attendee receiving the message.</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td>Attendee Ticket Type</td>
			<td>Adds the name of the ticket the attendee has purchased. For example, if the attendee purchased a ticket called “General Admission,” then that will be the name that is displayed in the message.</td>
		</tr>
	</tbody>
</table>
</div>    			
